{"title_page": "Luigi Palma di Cesnola", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n|name=Luigi Palma di Cesnola\n|birth_date= {{Birth date|1832|7|29}}\n|death_date= {{Death date and age|1904|11|20|1832|7|29}}\n|birth_place= [[Rivarolo Canavese]], [[Italy]]\n|death_place= [[New York City]]\n|placeofburial=[[Kensico Cemetery]]<br>[[Valhalla, New York]]\n|placeofburial_label= Place of burial\n|image= Luigi P. di Cesnola.jpg\n|caption= Cesnola circa 1900\n|nickname=\n|allegiance= {{Flag|Kingdom of Sardinia|1848}}<br/>{{flagcountry|UKGBI}}<br/>{{flagicon|USA|1861}} [[United States of America]]\n|branch={{flagicon|Kingdom of Sardinia|1848}} Sardinian Army<br>{{army|UKGBI}}<br/>{{army|USA}}<br />[[Union Army]]\n|serviceyears= 1849\u20131854 (Sardinia)<br>1854\u20131856 (UK)<br>1862\u20131865 (USA)\n|rank= [[File:Union Army colonel rank insignia.png|35px]] [[Colonel (United States)|Colonel]] ([[United States Volunteers|USA]])\n|commands=4th New York Cavalry\n|unit=\n|battles= [[First Italian War of Independence]]<br>[[Crimean War]]<br>[[American Civil War]]\n|awards= [[Medal of Honor]]\n|laterwork=\n}}\n\n'''Luigi Palma di Cesnola''' (July 29, 1832 \u2013 November 20, 1904), an [[Italian American|Italian-American]] soldier, diplomat and amateur [[Archaeology|archaeologist]], was born in [[Rivarolo Canavese]], near [[Turin]].  He received the [[Medal of Honor]] for his actions during the [[American Civil War]]. He was United States consul at [[Larnaca]] in [[Cyprus]] (1865\u20131877) and first Director of the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] in New York (1879\u20131904).<ref name=obit/>\n\n==Biography==\nLuigi Palma di Cesnola was born the second son of a count and military officer at [[Rivarolo Canavese]], Piedmont, in the [[Kingdom of Sardinia]], Italy.<ref name=ItaAmeExp>Aldo E. Salerno. In ''The Italian American Experience: An Encyclopedia'', ed. Salvatore J. LaGumina (New York: Garland, 2000), p.106</ref> His uncle was Italian patriot [[Alerino Palma]], and his brother was [[Alessandro Palma di Cesnola]].<ref name=CatMostra>Maria Luisa Moncassoli Tibone. \"Dal Piemonte a Cipro, a New York: un\u2019avventura appassionante\".</ref>\n\nIn 1848 Luigi joined the Sardinian army at the age of 15, and served in the [[First Italian War of Independence]].<ref name=CatMostra/> During the battle of Novara on 23 March 1849, he was decorated for bravery and promoted to the rank of [[second lieutenant]].<ref name=ItaAmeExp/> He graduated from the Royal Military Academy at [[Cherasco]] in 1851.<ref name=ItaAmeExp/> In 1854 he was dismissed for unknown reasons, and subsequently served with the [[British Army]] in the [[Crimean War]] as the aide-de-camp to General [[Enrico Fardella]].<ref name=CatMostra/>\n\nIn 1858 he went to [[New York City|New York]],<ref name=ItaAmeExp/><ref name=CatMostra/> where he first taught [[Italian language|Italian]] and [[French language|French]]. In February 1861 he married Mary Isabel Reid, the daughter of war hero Commodore [[Samuel Chester Reid]].<ref name=CatMostra/><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dictionaryofarthistorians.org/cesnolal.htm |title=Dictionary of Art Historians |access-date=2013-11-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930014552/http://www.dictionaryofarthistorians.org/cesnolal.htm |archive-date=2007-09-30 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He then founded a private military school for officers, where in six months he trained over seven hundred students.<ref name=ItaAmeExp/> Since 1862, he took part in the [[American Civil War]] as [[Colonel (United States)|colonel]] of the 4th New York Cavalry Regiment, serving under the name '''Louis P. di Cesnola'''. Accused of sending stolen property North, Cesnola was threatened with dishonorable dismissal from the army.<ref>National Archives, RG 94, Entry 297, U. S. War Department General Order No. 27, February 2, 1863</ref> However, at the [[Battle of Aldie]] (June 1863), Colonel di Cesnola was wounded and taken prisoner. He received a [[Medal of Honor]] for his efforts during the battle. He was released from [[Libby Prison]] early in 1864 when the Union Agent for Prisoner Exchange offered a personal friend of Jefferson Davis as barter.<ref>{{cite book|last=Elizabeth|first=Mcfadden|title=The Glitter and the Gold|year=1971|publisher=Dial Press|location=New York|pages=60}}</ref>  He served in the [[Battle of the Wilderness|Wilderness]] and [[Siege of Petersburg|Petersburg]] campaigns (1864\u201365) as a commander of a cavalry brigade but was not promoted to [[brigadier general]]. Although he was nominated for appointment to the [[Brevet (military)|brevet]] grade of brigadier general to rank from March 13, 1865 after the end of the war, the [[U.S. Senate]] never confirmed his appointment (contrary to the inscription on his grave stone).<ref>Eicher, John H., and [[David J. Eicher]], ''Civil War High Commands.'' Stanford: Stanford University Press, 2001. {{ISBN|0-8047-3641-3}}. p. 594</ref><ref>Also, di Cesnola's name is not listed in Hunt, Roger D. and Jack R. Brown, ''Brevet Brigadier Generals in Blue.'' Gaithersburg, MD: Olde Soldier Books, Inc., 1990. {{ISBN|1-56013-002-4}}.</ref>\n\n[[File:Louis Palma Di Cesnola Monument 2010.JPG|thumb|left|The burial location of Louis Palma Di Cesnola]]\nAfter the war, he was appointed United States [[Consul (representative)|consul]] at [[Larnaca]] in [[Cyprus]] (1865\u20131877). During his stay on Cyprus he carried out excavations (especially around the archaeological site of [[Kourion]]), which resulted in the discovery of a large number of antiquities. \nThe ''[[Napried]]'', one of the ships commissioned by di Cesnola to transport approximately 35,000 pieces of antiquities that he had collected from [[Cyprus]], was lost at sea carrying about 5,000 pieces in its cargo.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://napried.com/|title=Napried Exploration|website=napried.com|access-date=2019-06-22}}</ref>\nThe collection was purchased by the newly expanded [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] in New York in 1872, and Cesnola became the first director in 1879, until his death in 1904. Doubt having been thrown by the art critic [[Clarence Cook]],<ref>\"Clarence Cook Dead\", ''The New York Times'', June 3, 1900</ref> and by [[Gaston L. Feuardent]],<ref>\"Gaston L. Feuardent,\" ''The New York Times'', June 13, 1893</ref> in an article in the ''[[New York Herald]]'' (August 1880), upon the genuineness of his restorations, the matter was referred to a special committee, which pronounced in his favor. In [[Cyprus]] however, his actions are still considered to tantamount to looting.<ref>{{Cite news |first=Constantine |last=Markides |title=Taking stock of our stolen past |date=August 13, 2006 |url=http://www.archaeologynews.org/link.asp?ID=103579&Title=Taking%20stock%20of%20our%20stolen%20past |work=Archaeology News |accessdate=2007-04-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080112012336/http://www.archaeologynews.org/link.asp?ID=103579&Title=Taking%20stock%20of%20our%20stolen%20past |archivedate=January 12, 2008 }}</ref> Researcher Ahmet Gazio\u011flu, citing excerpts from di Cesnola's own book, wrote that di Cesnola often excavated illegally using blackmail and that he was \"a problem to the Turkish authorities, both because of his contempt for the law and his misbehaviour towards the officials and the people\".<ref>{{cite book|last1=Gazio\u011flu|first1=Ahmet C.|title=The Turks in Cyprus: A Province of the Ottoman Empire (1571-1878)|date=1990|publisher=K. Rustem & Brother|location=London|pages=225\u2013230}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Louis Palma Di Cesnola Footstone 2010.JPG|thumb|The footstone of Louis Palma Di Cesnola]]Cesnola was the author of ''Cyprus, its ancient Cities, Tombs and Temples'' (1877), a travel book of considerable service to the practical antiquary; and of a ''Descriptive Atlas of the Cesnola Collection of Cypriote Antiquities'' (3 volumes, 1884\u20131886). He received honorary degrees from Columbia and Princeton universities and a special knightly order from the king of Italy,<ref name=ItaAmeExp/> and was a member of several learned societies in Europe and America.\n\nHe died in New York City on November 20, 1904.<ref name=obit>{{cite news |title=Gen. Di Cesnola Dies After Short Illness. Director of Metropolitan Museum of Art for Twenty-five Years. Made Cypriote Collection. Honored for Gallant Service in Civil War. Also Veteran of Austrian and Crimean Wars |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9807E2DE163DE733A25751C2A9679D946597D6CF |quote=Gen. Louis Palma Di Cesnola, Director of the Metropolitan Museum of Art since 1879, died suddenly and after a very short illness on Sunday night at his residence, the Hotel Seymour, 44 West Forty-fifth Street. After his usual day's work at the museum on Friday the General attended the dinner of the Eleventh Army Corps in the evening, and left the banquet hall apparently in his usual health. ... |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |date=November 22, 1904 |accessdate=2013-12-23 }}</ref> He was interred at [[Kensico Cemetery]] in [[Valhalla, NY]]. His funerals, on 23 November 1904 at [[St. Patrick's Cathedral (Manhattan)]], were attended by a crowd of more than 2000 dignitaries and mourners.<ref>Gioachino Toesca di Castellazzo, ''Commemorazione del generale Luigi Palma di Cesnola'' (Torino: Cassone, 1905)</ref>\n\n==Medal of Honor citation==\n[[File:DoV1-214 - Capture of Luigi P. di Cesnola.jpg|thumb|di Cesnola is captured during the Battle of Aldie, from ''Deeds of Valor'']]\nRank and organization: Colonel, 4th New York Cavalry. Place and date: At Aldie, Va., June 17, 1863. Entered service at: New York, N.Y. Born: June 29, 1832, Rivarolo Canavese, Turin, Piedmont, Italy. Date of issue: Unknown.\n\nAt the start of the battle at Aldie, Cesnola was placed under arrest by his superior officer for protesting the promotion of a less experienced officer to brigadier general.  He was stripped of his saber and sidearm.  Without Cesnola the Fourth New York Cavalry balked repeatedly when asked to charge a hillside gun battery.  The commanding general knew Cesnola was needed to rally the unit.  He said, \"Colonel, you are a brave man.  You are released from arrest.  Here is my own sword.  Take it and bring it back to me covered in the enemy's blood.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Beyer|first=Walter F.|title=Deeds of Valor|year=1907|publisher=National Archives|pages=211\u2013212|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kp7hAAAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=deeds+of+valor&hl=en&ei=IZJxTYyJHIP78AaqpMW_Dw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCgQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>   When he entered the battle \"the regiment arrived on the scene of conflict, and by a gallant charge, turned apparent defeat into a glorious victory for our arms, completely routing the enemy and cutting off nearly 100 men, all of whom were captured.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=The Fourth New York Cavalry, A Record of Its Services|newspaper=The New York Times|date=September 25, 1864}}</ref>   At the close of the battle Cesnola was found in a field lying under his own horse, wounded on the head by a saber and on the arm by a minie ball.<ref>{{cite book|last=Mcfadden|first=Elizabeth|title=The Glitter and the Gold|year=1971|publisher=Dial Press|location=New York}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|American Civil War}}\n*[[List of Medal of Honor recipients for the Battle of Gettysburg]]\n*[[List of Italian American Medal of Honor recipients]]\n*[[List of American Civil War Medal of Honor recipients: A\u2013F]]\n*[[Italian Americans in the Civil War]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n* Giuseppe Giacosa, ''Impressioni d'America'' (Milano: Cogliati, 1898; 2nd ed. 1902) \n* Gioachino Toesca di Castellazzo, ''Commemorazione del generale Luigi Palma di Cesnola'' (Torino: Cassone, 1905)\n* Hunt, Roger D. and Jack R. Brown, ''Brevet Brigadier Generals in Blue.'' Gaithersburg, MD: Olde Soldier Books, Inc., 1990. {{ISBN|1-56013-002-4}}.\n* Mcfadden, Elizabeth.  ''The Glitter and the Gold: A Spirited Account of the Metropolitan Museum of Art's First Director, the Audacious and High-Handed Luigi Palma di Cesnola''  New York: Dial Press, 1971.\n* {{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Cesnola, Luigi Palma di}}\n* Robert Cole. \"A Cavalryman First.\" In ''They Made It in America'' (New York: Morrow, 1993) 12\u201315.\n* Aldo E. Salerno. \"Luigi Palma di Cesnola.\" In ''The Italian American Experience: An Encyclopedia'', ed. Salvatore J. LaGumina (New York: Garland, 2000), p.&nbsp;106\n* Eicher, John H., and [[David J. Eicher]], ''Civil War High Commands.'' Stanford: Stanford University Press, 2001. {{ISBN|0-8047-3641-3}}.\n* Maria Luisa Moncassoli Tibone. \"Dal Piemonte a Cipro, a New York: un\u2019avventura appassionante\". In ''Catalogo della mostra'' \"Luigi Palma di Cesnola. Le gesta di un Piemontese dagli scavi di Cipro al Metropolitan Museum.\" \u2013 Palazzo Lascaris, 12 novembre \u2013 11 dicembre 2004'' (Torino, 2004), pp.&nbsp;9\u201319 [http://www.cr.piemonte.it/dwd/pubblicazioni/tascabili/cesnola/cesnola.pdf Online edition]\n*{{Cite Appletons'|wstitle=Cesnola, Luigi Palma di|year=1891  }}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |author1=Hermary, Antoine  |author2=Mertens, Joan R.  |lastauthoramp=yes | title= The Cesnola collection of Cypriot art: stone sculpture | location=New York | publisher=The Metropolitan Museum of Art | year=2014 | isbn=9780300206715 | url= http://libmma.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/compoundobject/collection/p15324coll10/id/162840}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://libmma.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/search/field/subjec/searchterm/Cesnola,%20Luigi%20Palma%20di,%201832-1904%20--%20Art%20collections%20--%20Guidebooks/mode/exact Digitized Guides to the Cesnola Collection] from The Metropolitan Museum of Art Libraries\n*[https://libmma.contentdm.oclc.org/digital/collection/p15324coll13/id/16283 Luigi Palma di Cesnola collection, 1861-1950s (bulk, 1861-1904)] in The Metropolitan Museum of Art Archives\n* [https://archives-manuscripts.dartmouth.edu/repositories/2/resources/1778 The Papers of Luigi Cesnola] at Dartmouth College Library\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-culture}}\n{{Succession box\n  |title  = [[File:Metropolitan Museum of Art by Simon Fieldhouse.jpg|44px]]<br/>[[List of Directors of the Metropolitan Museum of Art|Director of the Metropolitan Museum of Art]]\n  |years  = 1879\u20131904\n  |before = \u2013\n  |after  = [[Caspar Purdon Clarke]]\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Palma di Cesnola, Luigi}}\n[[Category:1832 births]]\n[[Category:1904 deaths]]\n[[Category:Italian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:People of New York (state) in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:Union Army colonels]]\n[[Category:American Civil War prisoners of war]]\n[[Category:United States Army Medal of Honor recipients]]\n[[Category:Italian archaeologists]]\n[[Category:American archaeologists]]\n[[Category:Directors of the Metropolitan Museum of Art]]\n[[Category:Foreign-born Medal of Honor recipients]]\n[[Category:American Civil War recipients of the Medal of Honor]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military person\n|name=Luigi Palma di Cesnola\n|birth_date= {{Birth date|1832|7|29}}\n|death_date= {{Death date and age|1904|11|20|1832|7|29}}\n|birth_place= [[Rivarolo Canavese]], [[Italy]]\n|death_place= [[New York City]]\n|placeofburial=[[Kensico Cemetery]]<br>[[Valhalla, New York]]\n|placeofburial_label= Place of burial\n|image= Luigi P. di Cesnola.jpg\n|caption= Cesnola circa 1900\n|nickname=\n|allegiance= {{Flag|Kingdom of Sardinia|1848}}<br/>{{flagcountry|UKGBI}}<br/>{{flagicon|USA|1861}} [[United States of America]]\n|branch={{flagicon|Kingdom of Sardinia|1848}} Sardinian Army<br>{{army|UKGBI}}<br/>{{army|USA}}<br />[[Union Army]]\n|serviceyears= 1849\u20131854 (Sardinia)<br>1854\u20131856 (UK)<br>1862\u20131865 (USA)\n|rank= [[File:Union Army colonel rank insignia.png|35px]] [[Colonel (United States)|Colonel]] ([[United States Volunteers|USA]])\n|commands=4th New York Cavalry\n|unit=\n|battles= [[First Italian War of Independence]]<br>[[Crimean War]]<br>[[American Civil War]]\n|awards= [[Medal of Honor]]\n|laterwork=\n}}\n\n'''Luigi Palma di Cesnola''' (July 29, 1832 \u2013 November 20, 1904), an [[Italian American|Italian-American]] soldier, diplomat and amateur [[Archaeology|archaeologist]], was born in [[Rivarolo Canavese]], near [[Turin]].  He received the [[Medal of Honor]] for his actions during the [[American Civil War]]. He was United States consul at [[Larnaca]] in [[Cyprus]] (1865\u20131877) and first Director of the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] in New York (1879\u20131904).<ref name=obit/>\n\n==Biography==\nLuigi Palma di Cesnola was born the second son of a count and military officer at [[Rivarolo Canavese]], Piedmont, in the [[Kingdom of Sardinia]], Italy.<ref name=ItaAmeExp>Aldo E. Salerno. In ''The Italian American Experience: An Encyclopedia'', ed. Salvatore J. LaGumina (New York: Garland, 2000), p.106</ref> His uncle was Italian patriot [[Alerino Palma]], and his brother was [[Alessandro Palma di Cesnola]].<ref name=CatMostra>Maria Luisa Moncassoli Tibone. \"Dal Piemonte a Cipro, a New York: un\u2019avventura appassionante\".</ref>\n\nIn 1848 Luigi joined the Sardinian army at the age of 15, and served in the [[First Italian War of Independence]].<ref name=CatMostra/> During the battle of Novara on 23 March 1849, he was decorated for bravery and promoted to the rank of [[second lieutenant]].<ref name=ItaAmeExp/> He graduated from the Royal Military Academy at [[Cherasco]] in 1851.<ref name=ItaAmeExp/> In 1854 he was dismissed for unknown reasons, and subsequently served with the [[British Army]] in the [[Crimean War]] as the aide-de-camp to General [[Enrico Fardella]].<ref name=CatMostra/>\n\nIn 1858 he went to [[New York City|New York]],<ref name=ItaAmeExp/><ref name=CatMostra/> where he first taught [[Italian language|Italian]] and [[French language|French]]. In February 1861 he married Mary Isabel Reid, the daughter of war hero Commodore [[Samuel Chester Reid]].<ref name=CatMostra/><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dictionaryofarthistorians.org/cesnolal.htm |title=Dictionary of Art Historians |access-date=2013-11-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930014552/http://www.dictionaryofarthistorians.org/cesnolal.htm |archive-date=2007-09-30 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He then founded a private military school for officers, where in six months he trained over seven hundred students.<ref name=ItaAmeExp/> Since 1862, he took part in the [[American Civil War]] as [[Colonel (United States)|colonel]] of the 4th New York Cavalry Regiment, serving under the name '''Louis P. di Cesnola'''. Accused of sending stolen property North, Cesnola was threatened with dishonorable dismissal from the army.<ref>National Archives, RG 94, Entry 297, U. S. War Department General Order No. 27, February 2, 1863</ref> However, at the [[Battle of Aldie]] (June 1863), Colonel di Cesnola was wounded and taken prisoner. He received a [[Medal of Honor]] for his efforts during the battle. He was released from [[Libby Prison]] early in 1864 when the Union Agent for Prisoner Exchange offered a personal friend of Jefferson Davis as barter.<ref>{{cite book|last=Elizabeth|first=Mcfadden|title=The Glitter and the Gold|year=1971|publisher=Dial Press|location=New York|pages=60}}</ref>  He served in the [[Battle of the Wilderness|Wilderness]] and [[Siege of Petersburg|Petersburg]] campaigns (1864\u201365) as a commander of a cavalry brigade but was not promoted to [[brigadier general]]. Although he was nominated for appointment to the [[Brevet (military)|brevet]] grade of brigadier general to rank from March 13, 1865 after the end of the war, the [[U.S. Senate]] never confirmed his appointment (contrary to the inscription on his grave stone).<ref>Eicher, John H., and [[David J. Eicher]], ''Civil War High Commands.'' Stanford: Stanford University Press, 2001. {{ISBN|0-8047-3641-3}}. p. 594</ref><ref>Also, di Cesnola's name is not listed in Hunt, Roger D. and Jack R. Brown, ''Brevet Brigadier Generals in Blue.'' Gaithersburg, MD: Olde Soldier Books, Inc., 1990. {{ISBN|1-56013-002-4}}.</ref>\n\n[[File:Louis Palma Di Cesnola Monument 2010.JPG|thumb|left|The burial location of Louis Palma Di Cesnola]]\nAfter the war, he was appointed United States [[Consul (representative)|consul]] at [[Larnaca]] in [[Cyprus]] (1865\u20131877). During his stay on Cyprus he carried out excavations (especially around the archaeological site of [[Kourion]]), which resulted in the discovery of a large number of antiquities. \nThe ''[[Napried]]'', one of the ships commissioned by di Cesnola to transport approximately 35,000 pieces of antiquities that he had collected from [[Cyprus]], was lost at sea carrying about 5,000 pieces in its cargo.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://napried.com/|title=Napried Exploration|website=napried.com|access-date=2019-06-22}}</ref>\nThe collection was purchased by the newly expanded [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] in New York in 1872, and Cesnola became the first director in 1879, until his death in 1904. Doubt having been thrown by the art critic [[Clarence Cook]],<ref>\"Clarence Cook Dead\", ''The New York Times'', June 3, 1900</ref> and by [[Gaston L. Feuardent]],<ref>\"Gaston L. Feuardent,\" ''The New York Times'', June 13, 1893</ref> in an article in the ''[[New York Herald]]'' (August 1880), upon the genuineness of his restorations, the matter was referred to a special committee, which pronounced in his favor. In [[Cyprus]] however, his actions are still considered to tantamount to looting.<ref>{{Cite news |first=Constantine |last=Markides |title=Taking stock of our stolen past |date=August 13, 2006 |url=http://www.archaeologynews.org/link.asp?ID=103579&Title=Taking%20stock%20of%20our%20stolen%20past |work=Archaeology News |accessdate=2007-04-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080112012336/http://www.archaeologynews.org/link.asp?ID=103579&Title=Taking%20stock%20of%20our%20stolen%20past |archivedate=January 12, 2008 }}</ref> Researcher Ahmet Gazio\u011flu, citing excerpts from di Cesnola's own book, wrote that di Cesnola often excavated illegally using blackmail and that he was \"a problem to the Turkish authorities, both because of his contempt for the law and his misbehaviour towards the officials and the people\".<ref>{{cite book|last1=Gazio\u011flu|first1=Ahmet C.|title=The Turks in Cyprus: A Province of the Ottoman Empire (1571-1878)|date=1990|publisher=K. Rustem & Brother|location=London|pages=225\u2013230}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Louis Palma Di Cesnola Footstone 2010.JPG|thumb|The footstone of Louis Palma Di Cesnola]]Cesnola was the author of ''Cyprus, its ancient Cities, Tombs and Temples'' (1877), a travel book of considerable service to the practical antiquary; and of a ''Descriptive Atlas of the Cesnola Collection of Cypriote Antiquities'' (3 volumes, 1884\u20131886). He received honorary degrees from Columbia and Princeton universities and a special knightly order from the king of Italy,<ref name=ItaAmeExp/> and was a member of several learned societies in Europe and America.\n\nHe died in New York City on November 20, 1904.<ref name=obit>{{cite news |title=Gen. Di Cesnola Dies After Short Illness. Director of Metropolitan Museum of Art for Twenty-five Years. Made Cypriote Collection. Honored for Gallant Service in Civil War. Also Veteran of Austrian and Crimean Wars |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9807E2DE163DE733A25751C2A9679D946597D6CF |quote=Gen. Louis Palma Di Cesnola, Director of the Metropolitan Museum of Art since 1879, died suddenly and after a very short illness on Sunday night at his residence, the Hotel Seymour, 44 West Forty-fifth Street. After his usual day's work at the museum on Friday the General attended the dinner of the Eleventh Army Corps in the evening, and left the banquet hall apparently in his usual health. ... |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |date=November 22, 1904 |accessdate=2013-12-23 }}</ref> He was interred at [[Kensico Cemetery]] in [[Valhalla, NY]]. His funerals, on 23 November 1904 at [[St. Patrick's Cathedral (Manhattan)]], were attended by a crowd of more than 2000 dignitaries and mourners.<ref>Gioachino Toesca di Castellazzo, ''Commemorazione del generale Luigi Palma di Cesnola'' (Torino: Cassone, 1905)</ref>\n\n==Medal of Honor citation==\n[[File:DoV1-214 - Capture of Luigi P. di Cesnola.jpg|thumb|di Cesnola is captured during the Battle of Aldie, from ''Deeds of Valor'']]\nRank and organization: Colonel, 4th New York Cavalry. Place and date: At Aldie, Va., June 17, 1863. Entered service at: New York, N.Y. Born: June 29, 1832, Rivarolo Canavese, Turin, Piedmont, Italy. Date of issue: Unknown.\n\nAt the start of the battle at Aldie, Cesnola was placed under arrest by his superior officer for protesting the promotion of a less experienced officer to brigadier general.  He was stripped of his saber and sidearm.  Without Cesnola the Fourth New York Cavalry balked repeatedly when asked to charge a hillside gun battery.  The commanding general knew Cesnola was needed to rally the unit.  He said, \"Colonel, you are a brave man.  You are released from arrest.  Here is my own sword.  Take it and bring it back to me covered in the enemy's blood.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Beyer|first=Walter F.|title=Deeds of Valor|year=1907|publisher=National Archives|pages=211\u2013212|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kp7hAAAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=deeds+of+valor&hl=en&ei=IZJxTYyJHIP78AaqpMW_Dw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCgQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>   When he entered the battle \"the regiment arrived on the scene of conflict, and by a gallant charge, turned apparent defeat into a glorious victory for our arms, completely routing the enemy and cutting off nearly 100 men, all of whom were captured.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=The Fourth New York Cavalry, A Record of Its Services|newspaper=The New York Times|date=September 25, 1864}}</ref>   At the close of the battle Cesnola was found in a field lying under his own horse, wounded on the head by a saber and on the arm by a minie ball.<ref>{{cite book|last=Mcfadden|first=Elizabeth|title=The Glitter and the Gold|year=1971|publisher=Dial Press|location=New York}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|American Civil War}}\n*[[List of Medal of Honor recipients for the Battle of Gettysburg]]\n*[[List of Italian American Medal of Honor recipients]]\n*[[List of American Civil War Medal of Honor recipients: A\u2013F]]\n*[[Italian Americans in the Civil War]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n* Giuseppe Giacosa, ''Impressioni d'America'' (Milano: Cogliati, 1898; 2nd ed. 1902) \n* Gioachino Toesca di Castellazzo, ''Commemorazione del generale Luigi Palma di Cesnola'' (Torino: Cassone, 1905)\n* Hunt, Roger D. and Jack R. Brown, ''Brevet Brigadier Generals in Blue.'' Gaithersburg, MD: Olde Soldier Books, Inc., 1990. {{ISBN|1-56013-002-4}}.\n* Mcfadden, Elizabeth.  ''The Glitter and the Gold: A Spirited Account of the Metropolitan Museum of Art's First Director, the Audacious and High-Handed Luigi Palma di Cesnola''  New York: Dial Press, 1971.\n* {{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Cesnola, Luigi Palma di}}\n* Robert Cole. \"A Cavalryman First.\" In ''They Made It in America'' (New York: Morrow, 1993) 12\u201315.\n* Aldo E. Salerno. \"Luigi Palma di Cesnola.\" In ''The Italian American Experience: An Encyclopedia'', ed. Salvatore J. LaGumina (New York: Garland, 2000), p.&nbsp;106\n* Eicher, John H., and [[David J. Eicher]], ''Civil War High Commands.'' Stanford: Stanford University Press, 2001. {{ISBN|0-8047-3641-3}}.\n* Maria Luisa Moncassoli Tibone. \"Dal Piemonte a Cipro, a New York: un\u2019avventura appassionante\". In ''Catalogo della mostra'' \"Luigi Palma di Cesnola. Le gesta di un Piemontese dagli scavi di Cipro al Metropolitan Museum.\" \u2013 Palazzo Lascaris, 12 novembre \u2013 11 dicembre 2004'' (Torino, 2004), pp.&nbsp;9