{"title_page": "Clement C. Dickinson", "text_new": "[[File:ClementCDickinson.jpg|thumb|Clement C. Dickinson]]\n\n'''Clement Cabell  Dickinson''' (December 6, 1849 \u2013 January 14, 1938), also known as '''Clement C. Dickinson''', was a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] [[United States House of Representatives|Representative]] representing [[Missouri]] from February 1, 1910, to March 3, 1921, from March 4, 1923 \u2013 March 3, 1929 and from March 4, 1931 \u2013 January 3, 1935.\n\nDickinson was born  at [[Prince Edward Court House, Virginia]] in [[Prince Edward County, Virginia]].  He graduated from [[Hampden-Sydney College]] in Virginia in 1869 and taught in Virginia and Kentucky.  He moved to [[Clinton, Missouri]] in 1872 where he continued to teach and study law.  He was prosecuting attorney in [[Henry County, Missouri]] 1876\u20131882, city attorney in Clinton 1882\u20131884, a member [[Missouri House of Representatives]] 1900-1902 and [[Missouri State Senate]] 1902\u20131906.  He was on the board of [[Central Missouri State University]] 1907\u20131913.\n\nHe was elected to Congress  to succeed [[David A. De Armond]]  who had died.  He failed to be re-elected in 1920 but served another two terms from 1931 to 1935 but was not renominated in 1934.  He is buried in Englewood Cemetery in Clinton.\n\n==References==\n\n{{CongBio|D000316}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n* {{Find a Grave|21757}}\n* [http://www.violetpress.com/book/mbf/default.htm] The extension of remarks read into the ''Congressional Record'' by Clement C. Dickenson in 1914 are included in ''A Tribute to the Best Friend of Man: Eulogy on the Dog'' printed by Violet Press in 2008.\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{US House succession box\n| state=Missouri\n| district=6\n| before=[[David A. De Armond]] | after=[[William O. Atkeson]]| years=1910&ndash;1921}}\n{{US House succession box\n| state=Missouri\n| district=6\n| before=[[William O. Atkeson]] | after=[[Thomas Jefferson Halsey]]| years=1923&ndash;1929}}\n{{US House succession box\n| state=Missouri\n| district=6\n| before=[[Thomas Jefferson Halsey]] | after=[[Reuben T. Wood]]| years=1931&ndash;1933}}\n{{US House succession box\n|state=Missouri\n| district=\n| before=None | after=None | years=1933&ndash;1935 (At-large)}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dickinson, Clement}}\n[[Category:1849 births]]\n[[Category:1938 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Prince Edward County, Virginia]]\n[[Category:People from Clinton, Missouri]]\n[[Category:Members of the Missouri House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Missouri state senators]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Missouri]]\n[[Category:Missouri Democrats]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n\n\n{{Missouri-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:ClementCDickinson.jpg|thumb|Clement C. Dickinson]]\n\n'''Clement Cabell  Dickinson''' (December 6, 1849 \u2013 January 14, 1938), also known as '''Clement C. Dickinson''', was a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] [[United States House of Representatives|Representative]] representing [[Missouri]] from February 1, 1910, to March 3, 1921, from March 4, 1923 \u2013 March 3, 1929 and from March 4, 1931 \u2013 January 3, 1935.\n\nDickinson was born  at [[Prince Edward Court House, Virginia]] in [[Prince Edward County, Virginia]].  He graduated from [[Hampden-Sydney College]] in Virginia in 1869 and taught in Virginia and Kentucky.  He moved to [[Clinton, Missouri]] in 1872 where he continued to teach and study law.  He was prosecuting attorney in [[Henry County, Missouri]] 1876-1882, city attorney in Clinton 1882-1884, a member [[Missouri House of Representatives]] 1900-1902 and [[Missouri State Senate]] 1902-1906.  He was on the board of [[Central Missouri State University]] 1907-1913.\n\nHe was elected to Congress  to succeed [[David A. De Armond]]  who had died.  He failed to be re-elected in 1920 but served another two terms from 1931 to 1935 but was not renominated in 1934.  He is buried in Englewood Cemetery in Clinton.\n\n==References==\n\n{{CongBio|D000316}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n* {{Find a Grave|21757}}\n* [http://www.violetpress.com/book/mbf/default.htm] The extension of remarks read into the ''Congressional Record'' by Clement C. Dickenson in 1914 are included in ''A Tribute to the Best Friend of Man: Eulogy on the Dog'' printed by Violet Press in 2008.\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{US House succession box\n| state=Missouri\n| district=6\n| before=[[David A. De Armond]] | after=[[William O. Atkeson]]| years=1910&ndash;1921}}\n{{US House succession box\n| state=Missouri\n| district=6\n| before=[[William O. Atkeson]] | after=[[Thomas Jefferson Halsey]]| years=1923&ndash;1929}}\n{{US House succession box\n| state=Missouri\n| district=6\n| before=[[Thomas Jefferson Halsey]] | after=[[Reuben T. Wood]]| years=1931&ndash;1933}}\n{{US House succession box\n|state=Missouri\n| district=\n| before=None | after=None | years=1933&ndash;1935 (At-large)}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dickinson, Clement}}\n[[Category:1849 births]]\n[[Category:1938 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Prince Edward County, Virginia]]\n[[Category:People from Clinton, Missouri]]\n[[Category:Members of the Missouri House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Missouri state senators]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Missouri]]\n[[Category:Missouri Democrats]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n\n\n{{Missouri-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1876-1882 \u2192 1876\u20131882 (4)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clement_C._Dickinson"}
{"title_page": "Weroance", "text_new": "{{see also|Sachem|Cacique}}\n'''Weroance''' is an [[Algonquian languages|Algonquian]] word meaning leader or commander among the [[Powhatan]] confederacy of the [[Virginia]] coast and [[Chesapeake Bay]] region. Weroances were under a paramount chief called Powhatan. The [[Powhatan Confederacy]], encountered by the colonists of [[Jamestown, Virginia|Jamestown]] and adjacent area of the [[Virginia Colony]] beginning in 1607, spoke an [[Algonquian languages|Algonquian]] language. Each tribe of the Powhatan Confederacy was led by its own weroance. Most foreign writers who have come across a weroance only did so on a special occasion. This is the case because a foreigners presence was special. John Smith noted that there are few differences between weroances and their subjects.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Rountree|first1=Helen C.|title=Pocahontas, Powhatan, Opechancanough : three Indian lives changed by Jamestown|date=2005|publisher=University of Virginia press|location=Charlottesville (Va.)|isbn=0-8139-2323-9|page=Chapter 2}}</ref>\n\nIn older texts, especially from the time of the early Jamestown settlers, spelling was not standardized, so the following spellings are used in different texts:\n* weeroance\n* weroance\n* werowance\n* werowans\n* wyroance\n* wyrounce\n* wyrounnces\nA '''weroansqua''' is a female ruler.  Spellings of this word also vary.\n\n==Powers of a weroance==\nParamount chiefs let their district and subordinate weroances make the final decision on how to handle a hostile situation. This was made apparent with the events that took place in 1607 and the hostility with the newcomers (English settlers). Weroances and Priest were the only ones allowed to enter into religious temples. A weroance did not go to meet any visitor, visitors were escorted to see a weroance. The weroance, their wives, and councilors often dressed in the finest jewels, and tanned deer skin.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Rountree|first1=Helen C.|title=Pocahontas, Powhatan, Opechancanough : three Indian lives changed by Jamestown|date=2005|publisher=University of Virginia press|location=Charlottesville (Va.)|isbn=0-8139-2323-9|page=Chapter 2}}</ref>\n\n==Individual weroances==\nSeveral of the weroances' personal names were known and some recorded by [[William Strachey]] and other sources.<ref>[http://www.mariner.org/chesapeakebay/native/nam031.html List of weroances recorded by Strachey]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080509192841/http://www.mariner.org/chesapeakebay/native/nam031.html |date=May 9, 2008 }}</ref> The names of their respective chieftaincies were also commonly used as titles, exactly analogous to European peerages, so that the Weroance of Arrohattec (whose given name was Ashaquid) was often referred to simply as \"Arrohattec\", much as the Earl of Essex would be referred to just as \"Essex\" in lieu of a personal name.\n\nWhen the English arrived in Virginia, some of the weroances subject to the paramount chief Powhatan, or ''mamanatowick'' (Wahunsenacawh) were his own nearest male relatives:\n\n* Parahunt, Weroance of the Powhatan (proper), also called ''Tanx'' (\"little\") Powhatan, said by Strachey to be a son of the paramount chief Powhatan, and often confused with same.\n* Pochins, Weroance of the [[Kecoughtan]], was also a son of the paramount chief, whom he had appointed there some time after slaying their previous ruler in ca. 1598.  \n*[[Opechancanough]], Chief Powhatan's younger brother, was a weroance of the [[Pamunkey]], but increased in power, and came to be the effective ruler of the entire Powhatan Confederacy after [[Wahunsenacawh]]'s death in 1618.\n\n==Matrilineal inheritance==\nIn Powhatan society, women could inherit power, because the inheritance of power was [[matrilineal]]. In ''A Map of Virginia'' [[John Smith of Jamestown]] explains:<blockquote>His <nowiki>[</nowiki>[[Chief Powhatan]]'s] kingdome descendeth not to his sonnes nor children: but first to his brethren, whereof he hath 3 namely [[Opitchapan]], [[Opechancanough]], and [[Catataugh]]; and after their decease to his sisters. First to the eldest sister, then to the rest: and after them to the heires male and female of the eldest sister; but never to the heires of the males.<ref>Smith, John. ''A Map of Virginia.'' Oxford: [[Joseph Barnes (printer)|Joseph Barnes]], 1612. [http://etext.lib.virginia.edu/etcbin/jamestown-browse?id=J1008 http://etext.lib.virginia.edu/etcbin/jamestown-browse?id=J1008], also Repr. in ''The Complete Works of John Smith (1580-1631)''. Ed. Philip L. Barbour. Chapel Hill: University Press of Virginia, 1983. Vol. 1, pp. 305-63.</ref></blockquote>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Rountree|first1=Helen C.|title=Pocahontas, Powhatan, Opechancanough : three Indian lives changed by Jamestown|date=2005|publisher=University of Virginia press|location=Charlottesville (Va.)|isbn=0-8139-2323-9|page=Chapter 2}}\n\n[[Category:Royal titles]]\n[[Category:Powhatan Confederacy]]\n[[Category:Titles and offices of Native American leaders]]\n[[Category:Tribal chiefs|*]]\n", "text_old": "{{see also|Sachem|Cacique}}\n'''Weroance''' is an [[Algonquian languages|Algonquian]] word meaning leader or commander among the [[Powhatan]] confederacy of the [[Virginia]] coast and [[Chesapeake Bay]] region. Weroances were under a paramount chief called Powhatan. The [[Powhatan Confederacy]], encountered by the colonists of [[Jamestown, Virginia|Jamestown]] and adjacent area of the [[Virginia Colony]] beginning in 1607, spoke an [[Algonquian languages|Algonquian]] language. Each tribe of the Powhatan Confederacy was led by its own weroance. Most foreign writers who have come across a weroance only did so on a special occasion. This is the case because a foreigners presence was special. John Smith noted that there are few differences between weroances and their subjects.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Rountree|first1=Helen C.|title=Pocahontas, Powhatan, Opechancanough : three Indian lives changed by Jamestown|date=2005|publisher=University of Virginia press|location=Charlottesville (Va.)|isbn=0-8139-2323-9|page=Chapter 2}}</ref>\n\nIn older texts, especially from the time of the early Jamestown settlers, spelling was not standardized, so the following spellings are used in different texts:\n* weeroance\n* weroance\n* werowance\n* werowans\n* wyroance\n* wyrounce\n* wyrounnces\nA '''weroansqua''' is a female ruler.  Spellings of this word also vary.\n\n==Powers of a weroance==\nParamount chiefs let their district and subordinate weroances make the final decision on how to handle a hostile situations. This was made apparent with the events that took place in 1607 and the hostility with the newcomers (English settlers). Weroances and Priest were the only ones allowed to enter into religious temples. A weroance did not go to meet any visitor, visitors were escorted to see a weroance. The weroance, their wives, and councilors often dressed in the finest jewels, and tanned deer skin.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Rountree|first1=Helen C.|title=Pocahontas, Powhatan, Opechancanough : three Indian lives changed by Jamestown|date=2005|publisher=University of Virginia press|location=Charlottesville (Va.)|isbn=0-8139-2323-9|page=Chapter 2}}</ref>\n\n==Individual weroances==\nSeveral of the weroances' personal names were known and some recorded by [[William Strachey]] and other sources.<ref>[http://www.mariner.org/chesapeakebay/native/nam031.html List of weroances recorded by Strachey]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080509192841/http://www.mariner.org/chesapeakebay/native/nam031.html |date=May 9, 2008 }}</ref> The names of their respective chieftaincies were also commonly used as titles, exactly analogous to European peerages, so that the Weroance of Arrohattec (whose given name was Ashaquid) was often referred to simply as \"Arrohattec\", much as the Earl of Essex would be referred to just as \"Essex\" in lieu of a personal name.\n\nWhen the English arrived in Virginia, some of the weroances subject to the paramount chief Powhatan, or ''mamanatowick'' (Wahunsenacawh) were his own nearest male relatives:\n\n* Parahunt, Weroance of the Powhatan (proper), also called ''Tanx'' (\"little\") Powhatan, said by Strachey to be a son of the paramount chief Powhatan, and often confused with same.\n* Pochins, Weroance of the [[Kecoughtan]], was also a son of the paramount chief, whom he had appointed there some time after slaying their previous ruler in ca. 1598.  \n*[[Opechancanough]], Chief Powhatan's younger brother, was a weroance of the [[Pamunkey]], but increased in power, and came to be the effective ruler of the entire Powhatan Confederacy after [[Wahunsenacawh]]'s death in 1618.\n\n==Matrilineal inheritance==\nIn Powhatan society, women could inherit power, because the inheritance of power was [[matrilineal]]. In ''A Map of Virginia'' [[John Smith of Jamestown]] explains:<blockquote>His <nowiki>[</nowiki>[[Chief Powhatan]]'s] kingdome descendeth not to his sonnes nor children: but first to his brethren, whereof he hath 3 namely [[Opitchapan]], [[Opechancanough]], and [[Catataugh]]; and after their decease to his sisters. First to the eldest sister, then to the rest: and after them to the heires male and female of the eldest sister; but never to the heires of the males.<ref>Smith, John. ''A Map of Virginia.'' Oxford: [[Joseph Barnes (printer)|Joseph Barnes]], 1612. [http://etext.lib.virginia.edu/etcbin/jamestown-browse?id=J1008 http://etext.lib.virginia.edu/etcbin/jamestown-browse?id=J1008], also Repr. in ''The Complete Works of John Smith (1580-1631)''. Ed. Philip L. Barbour. Chapel Hill: University Press of Virginia, 1983. Vol. 1, pp. 305-63.</ref></blockquote>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Rountree|first1=Helen C.|title=Pocahontas, Powhatan, Opechancanough : three Indian lives changed by Jamestown|date=2005|publisher=University of Virginia press|location=Charlottesville (Va.)|isbn=0-8139-2323-9|page=Chapter 2}}\n\n[[Category:Royal titles]]\n[[Category:Powhatan Confederacy]]\n[[Category:Titles and offices of Native American leaders]]\n[[Category:Tribal chiefs|*]]\n", "name_user": "Mildly Abrasive", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePowers of a weroance:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Weroance"}
{"title_page": "Crew Dragon Demo-2", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox spaceflight\n\n| name          = Crew Dragon Demo-2\n| image         = Demo-2 Crew Dragon.jpg\n| image_caption = The Crew Dragon to be used for Demo-2.\n| insignia      = [[File:Crew Dragon Demo-2 Patch.png|frameless|upright=0.6]]\n\n| mission_type       = \n| operator           = {{Hlist|[[NASA]]|[[SpaceX]]}}\n| COSPAR_ID          = \n| SATCAT             = \n| mission_duration   = \n| distance_travelled = \n| orbits_completed   = \n\n| spacecraft      = \n| spacecraft_type = [[Dragon 2|Crew Dragon]], [[Dragon 2#List of Dragon 2 capsules|C206]]\n| manufacturer    = [[SpaceX]]\n| launch_mass     = {{convert|NNNN|||abbr=on}}\n| landing_mass    = {{convert|NNNN|||abbr=on}}\n\n| launch_date   = 16 May 2020 NET<ref name=NJ>{{cite web|title=NASA, JAXA assign two more astronauts to second piloted Crew Dragon flight|url=https://spaceflightnow.com/2020/03/31/nasa-jaxa-assign-two-more-astronauts-to-second-piloted-crew-dragon-flight/|date=31 March 2020|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n| launch_rocket = [[Falcon 9 Full Thrust Block 5|Falcon 9]]\n| launch_site   = [[Kennedy Space Center Launch Complex 39|Kennedy Space Center, LC-39A]]\n| landing_date  = \n| landing_site  = \n\n| crew_size          = 2\n| crew_members       = [[Douglas G. Hurley]]<br/>[[Robert L. Behnken]]\n| crew_callsign      = \n| crew_photo         = [[File:SpaceX DM-2 Crew.jpg|180px]]\n| crew_photo_caption = \n\n| docking        = {{Infobox spaceflight/Dock\n| docking_target = [[International Space Station|ISS]]\n| docking_type   = dock\n| docking_port   = \n| docking_date   = \n| undocking_date = \n| time_docked    = \n}}\n| orbit_epoch       = \n| orbit_reference   = [[geocentric orbit|Geocentric]]\n| orbit_regime      = [[Low Earth orbit|Low Earth]]\n| orbit_periapsis   = \n| orbit_apoapsis    = \n| orbit_inclination = 51.6\u00b0 <!-- anticipated due to ISS mission --->\n| orbit_period      = \n| apsis             = gee\n\n| programme        = [[Commercial Crew Development]]\n| previous_mission = [[Dragon 2 In-Flight Abort Test]]\n| next_mission     = [[Boeing Orbital Flight Test 2]]\n}}\n\n'''Crew Dragon Demo-2''' (officially known as '''SpaceX Demo-2''' and '''Crew Demo-2''') will be the first crewed test flight of the [[Dragon 2|Crew Dragon]] spacecraft.<ref name=\"spnow\">{{cite web|url=https://spacexnow.com/upcoming.php|title=Upcoming Missions|website=spacexnow.com}}</ref> Currently scheduled for no earlier than 16 May 2020, Crew Dragon Demo-2 will be the first crewed orbital spaceflight launched from [[United States]] soil since [[STS-135]] in 2011, which Crew Dragon Demo-2's commander, [[Douglas G. Hurley|Douglas Hurley]], also flew.\n\n==Crew==\n{{Spaceflight crew\n|crew        = prime\n|terminology = Astronaut\n\n|position1   = Commander\n|crew1_up    = {{flagicon|USA}} [[Douglas G. Hurley]]\n|agency1_up  = [[NASA]]\n|flights1_up = Third\n\n|position2   = Pilot\n|crew2_up    = {{flagicon|USA}} [[Robert L. Behnken]]\n|agency2_up  = [[NASA]]\n|flights2_up = Third\n|notes       = Hurley and Behnken were announced as the crew on 3 August 2018.<ref name=nasa-20180803 />\n}}\n\n{{Spaceflight crew\n|crew = backup\n|terminology = Astronaut\n|references = <ref>{{Cite tweet |user=Commercial_Crew |number=1116404828656291840 |title=These four @NASA_Astronauts are training to fly on @SpaceX's #CrewDragon spacecraft- as the crew and backup crew. How have our astronauts been preparing for flight on @BoeingSpace and SpaceX's spacecraft |author=NASA Commercial Crew|date=April 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n|position1   = Commander\n|crew1_up    = {{flagicon|USA}} [[Michael S. Hopkins]]\n|agency1_up  = [[NASA]]\n|flights1_up = Second\n\n|position2   = Pilot\n|crew2_up    = {{flagicon|USA}} [[Victor J. Glover]]\n|agency2_up  = [[NASA]]\n|flights2_up = First\n}}\n\n==Mission==\nThe Crew Dragon Demo-2 mission was originally planned for launch in July 2019 as part of the [[Commercial Crew Development]] contract<ref name=\"NASAblogcc\">{{cite web |url=https://blogs.nasa.gov/commercialcrew/2019/02/06/nasa-partners-update-commercial-crew-launch-dates/|title=NASA's Commercial Crew Program Target Test Flight Dates|date=February 6, 2019|access-date=February 6, 2019}}</ref> with a crew of two on a 14-day test mission to the [[International Space Station]] (ISS).<ref name=\"nasa-20180803\">{{cite web|title=Meet the Astronauts Flying SpaceX's Demo-2 |url=https://blogs.nasa.gov/commercialcrew/2018/08/03/meet-the-astronauts-flying-spacexs-demo-2/|first=Marie|last=Lewis|date=3 August 2018|access-date=3 August 2018}}</ref> It is expected to be the first American spacecraft to fly crew into orbit since [[STS-135]] in July 2011. It would also be the first two-person American orbital spaceflight since [[STS-4]] in June 1982. Depending on the success of their respective test programs, this honor might go to the [[Boeing CST-100 Starliner]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://spaceflightnow.com/launch-schedule/|title=Launch Schedule \u2013 Spaceflight Now}}</ref> although this is unlikely since NASA has not decided whether Boeing needs to repeat another uncrewed test flight of Starliner<ref>{{cite web|last1=Grush|first1=Loren|title=Boeing's passenger spacecraft actually suffered a second unknown software glitch during debut flight|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/2/6/21127127/boeing-starliner-spacecraft-nasa-safety-software-glitch-catastrophic|website=The Verge|accessdate=24 February 2020}}</ref> and the Starliner's timeline is still on hold.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sheetz|first1=Michael|title=Boeing astronaut capsule Starliner faces further delays as NASA investigation continues |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/07/boeings-starliner-software-issues-under-nasa-investigation.html|website=CNBC|accessdate=24 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 20, 2019, the Crew Dragon capsule from the [[Crew Dragon Demo-1]] mission was destroyed during static fire testing of its [[SuperDraco]] thrusters, ahead of its planned use for an in-flight abort test.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Baylor|first1=Michael|title=SpaceX's Crew Dragon spacecraft suffers an anomaly during static fire testing at Cape Canaveral \u2013 NASASpaceFlight.com |url=https://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2019/04/spacexs-crew-dragon-spacecraft-anomaly-static-fire-testing/|work=NASASpaceFlight.com|date=April 20, 2019}}</ref><ref name=berger-20190502>{{cite news |last1=Berger|first1=Eric|title=Dragon was destroyed just before the firing of its SuperDraco thrusters|url=https://arstechnica.com/science/2019/05/dragon-was-destroyed-just-before-the-firing-of-its-superdraco-thrusters/|work=Ars Technica|date=May 2, 2019|language=en-us}}</ref> SpaceX traced the cause of the static fire anomaly to a valve that leaked propellant into high pressure helium lines.\n\nOn 19 January 2020, a Crew Dragon capsule successfully completed an in-flight abort test.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://spaceflightnow.com/2020/01/17/falcon-9-crew-dragon-in-flight-abort-test-mission-status-center/|title=Live coverage: SpaceX successfully performs Crew Dragon abort test \u2013 Spaceflight Now|first=Stephen|last=Clark}}</ref> The Crew Dragon Demo-2 mission could now launch no earlier than 16 May 2020.<ref name=NJ />\n\nOn 2 April 2020, NASA announced that the [[Falcon 9]] rocket carrying the Crew Dragon would feature NASA's iconic worm logo, the first time it has been used since it was retired in 1992.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dunbar |first1=Brian |title=The Worm is Back! |url=https://www.nasa.gov/feature/the-worm-is-back |website=NASA |publisher=NASA |accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Insignia==\nThe mission insignia was designed by Andrew Nyberg, an artist from [[Brainerd, Minnesota]]. Nyberg is a nephew of Hurley.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Murray|first1=Robb|title=Mankato native designed patch for upcoming NASA mission to the International Space Station|url=https://www.mankatofreepress.com/news/lifestyles/mankato-native-designed-patch-for-upcoming-nasa-mission-to-the/article_6006ed9e-0427-11ea-a9e7-63196804a071.html|website=Mankato Free Press|accessdate=14 November 2019|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Boeing Crewed Flight Test]], Boeing's first crewed mission of their capsule\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Portal|Spaceflight}}\n{{Manned ISS flights}}\n{{Dragon spaceflights}}\n{{Falcon rocket launches}}\n{{Future spaceflights}}\n\n[[Category:Dragon 2]]\n[[Category:2020 in spaceflight]]\n[[Category:SpaceX payloads contracted by NASA]]\n[[Category:SpaceX human spaceflights]]\n[[Category:Future human spaceflights]]\n[[Category:2020 in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox spaceflight\n\n| name          = Crew Dragon Demo-2\n| image         = Demo-2 Crew Dragon.jpg\n| image_caption = The Crew Dragon to be used for Demo-2.\n| insignia      = [[File:Crew Dragon Demo-2 Patch.png|frameless|upright=0.6]]\n\n| mission_type       = \n| operator           = {{Hlist|[[NASA]]|[[SpaceX]]}}\n| COSPAR_ID          = \n| SATCAT             = \n| mission_duration   = \n| distance_travelled = \n| orbits_completed   = \n\n| spacecraft      = \n| spacecraft_type = [[Dragon 2|Crew Dragon]], [[Dragon 2#List of Dragon 2 capsules|C206]]\n| manufacturer    = [[SpaceX]]\n| launch_mass     = {{convert|NNNN|||abbr=on}}\n| landing_mass    = {{convert|NNNN|||abbr=on}}\n\n| launch_date   = 16 May 2020 NET<ref>{{cite web|title=NASA, JAXA assign two more astronauts to second piloted Crew Dragon flight|url=https://spaceflightnow.com/2020/03/31/nasa-jaxa-assign-two-more-astronauts-to-second-piloted-crew-dragon-flight/|date=31 March 2020|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n| launch_rocket = [[Falcon 9 Full Thrust Block 5|Falcon 9]]\n| launch_site   = [[Kennedy Space Center Launch Complex 39|Kennedy Space Center, LC-39A]]\n| landing_date  = \n| landing_site  = \n\n| crew_size          = 2\n| crew_members       = [[Douglas G. Hurley]]<br/>[[Robert L. Behnken]]\n| crew_callsign      = \n| crew_photo         = [[File:SpaceX DM-2 Crew.jpg|180px]]\n| crew_photo_caption = \n\n| docking        = {{Infobox spaceflight/Dock\n| docking_target = [[International Space Station|ISS]]\n| docking_type   = dock\n| docking_port   = \n| docking_date   = \n| undocking_date = \n| time_docked    = \n}}\n| orbit_epoch       = \n| orbit_reference   = [[geocentric orbit|Geocentric]]\n| orbit_regime      = [[Low Earth orbit|Low Earth]]\n| orbit_periapsis   = \n| orbit_apoapsis    = \n| orbit_inclination = 51.6\u00b0 <!-- anticipated due to ISS mission --->\n| orbit_period      = \n| apsis             = gee\n\n| programme        = [[Commercial Crew Development]]\n| previous_mission = [[Dragon 2 In-Flight Abort Test]]\n| next_mission     = [[Boeing Orbital Flight Test 2]]\n}}\n\n'''Crew Dragon Demo-2''' (officially known as '''SpaceX Demo-2''' and '''Crew Demo-2''') will be the first crewed test flight of the [[Dragon 2|Crew Dragon]] spacecraft.<ref name=\"spnow\">{{cite web|url=https://spacexnow.com/upcoming.php|title=Upcoming Missions|website=spacexnow.com}}</ref> Currently scheduled for no earlier than 16 May 2020, Crew Dragon Demo-2 will be the first crewed orbital spaceflight launched from [[United States]] soil since [[STS-135]] in 2011, which Crew Dragon Demo-2's commander, [[Douglas G. Hurley|Douglas Hurley]], also flew.\n\n==Crew==\n{{Spaceflight crew\n|crew        = prime\n|terminology = Astronaut\n\n|position1   = Commander\n|crew1_up    = {{flagicon|USA}} [[Douglas G. Hurley]]\n|agency1_up  = [[NASA]]\n|flights1_up = Third\n\n|position2   = Pilot\n|crew2_up    = {{flagicon|USA}} [[Robert L. Behnken]]\n|agency2_up  = [[NASA]]\n|flights2_up = Third\n|notes       = Hurley and Behnken were announced as the crew on 3 August 2018.<ref name=nasa-20180803 />\n}}\n\n{{Spaceflight crew\n|crew = backup\n|terminology = Astronaut\n|references = <ref>{{Cite tweet |user=Commercial_Crew |number=1116404828656291840 |title=These four @NASA_Astronauts are training to fly on @SpaceX's #CrewDragon spacecraft- as the crew and backup crew. How have our astronauts been preparing for flight on @BoeingSpace and SpaceX's spacecraft |author=NASA Commercial Crew|date=April 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n|position1   = Commander\n|crew1_up    = {{flagicon|USA}} [[Michael S. Hopkins]]\n|agency1_up  = [[NASA]]\n|flights1_up = Second\n\n|position2   = Pilot\n|crew2_up    = {{flagicon|USA}} [[Victor J. Glover]]\n|agency2_up  = [[NASA]]\n|flights2_up = First\n}}\n\n==Mission==\nThe Crew Dragon Demo-2 mission was originally planned for launch in July 2019 as part of the [[Commercial Crew Development]] contract<ref name=\"NASAblogcc\">{{cite web |url=https://blogs.nasa.gov/commercialcrew/2019/02/06/nasa-partners-update-commercial-crew-launch-dates/|title=NASA's Commercial Crew Program Target Test Flight Dates|date=February 6, 2019|access-date=February 6, 2019}}</ref> with a crew of two on a 14-day test mission to the [[International Space Station]] (ISS).<ref name=\"nasa-20180803\">{{cite web|title=Meet the Astronauts Flying SpaceX's Demo-2 |url=https://blogs.nasa.gov/commercialcrew/2018/08/03/meet-the-astronauts-flying-spacexs-demo-2/|first=Marie|last=Lewis|date=3 August 2018|access-date=3 August 2018}}</ref> It is expected to be the first American spacecraft to fly crew into orbit since [[STS-135]] in July 2011. It would also be the first two-person American orbital spaceflight since [[STS-4]] in June 1982. Depending on the success of their respective test programs, this honor might go to the [[Boeing CST-100 Starliner]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://spaceflightnow.com/launch-schedule/|title=Launch Schedule \u2013 Spaceflight Now}}</ref> although this is unlikely since NASA has not decided whether Boeing needs to repeat another uncrewed test flight of Starliner<ref>{{cite web|last1=Grush|first1=Loren|title=Boeing's passenger spacecraft actually suffered a second unknown software glitch during debut flight|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/2/6/21127127/boeing-starliner-spacecraft-nasa-safety-software-glitch-catastrophic|website=The Verge|accessdate=24 February 2020}}</ref> and the Starliner's timeline is still on hold.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sheetz|first1=Michael|title=Boeing astronaut capsule Starliner faces further delays as NASA investigation continues |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/07/boeings-starliner-software-issues-under-nasa-investigation.html|website=CNBC|accessdate=24 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 20, 2019, the Crew Dragon capsule from the [[Crew Dragon Demo-1]] mission was destroyed during static fire testing of its [[SuperDraco]] thrusters, ahead of its planned use for an in-flight abort test.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Baylor|first1=Michael|title=SpaceX's Crew Dragon spacecraft suffers an anomaly during static fire testing at Cape Canaveral \u2013 NASASpaceFlight.com |url=https://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2019/04/spacexs-crew-dragon-spacecraft-anomaly-static-fire-testing/|work=NASASpaceFlight.com|date=April 20, 2019}}</ref><ref name=berger-20190502>{{cite news |last1=Berger|first1=Eric|title=Dragon was destroyed just before the firing of its SuperDraco thrusters|url=https://arstechnica.com/science/2019/05/dragon-was-destroyed-just-before-the-firing-of-its-superdraco-thrusters/|work=Ars Technica|date=May 2, 2019|language=en-us}}</ref> SpaceX traced the cause of the static fire anomaly to a valve that leaked propellant into high pressure helium lines.\n\nOn 19 January 2020, a Crew Dragon capsule successfully completed an in-flight abort test.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://spaceflightnow.com/2020/01/17/falcon-9-crew-dragon-in-flight-abort-test-mission-status-center/|title=Live coverage: SpaceX successfully performs Crew Dragon abort test \u2013 Spaceflight Now|first=Stephen|last=Clark}}</ref> The Crew Dragon Demo-2 mission could now launch no earlier than 16 May 2020.<ref>{{cite web|title=NASA, JAXA assign two more astronauts to second piloted Crew Dragon flight|url=https://spaceflightnow.com/2020/03/31/nasa-jaxa-assign-two-more-astronauts-to-second-piloted-crew-dragon-flight/|date=31 March 2020|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 April 2020, NASA announced that the [[Falcon 9]] rocket carrying the Crew Dragon would feature NASA's iconic worm logo, the first time it has been used since it was retired in 1992.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dunbar |first1=Brian |title=The Worm is Back! |url=https://www.nasa.gov/feature/the-worm-is-back |website=NASA |publisher=NASA |accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Insignia==\nThe mission insignia was designed by Andrew Nyberg, an artist from [[Brainerd, Minnesota]]. Nyberg is a nephew of Hurley.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Murray|first1=Robb|title=Mankato native designed patch for upcoming NASA mission to the International Space Station|url=https://www.mankatofreepress.com/news/lifestyles/mankato-native-designed-patch-for-upcoming-nasa-mission-to-the/article_6006ed9e-0427-11ea-a9e7-63196804a071.html|website=Mankato Free Press|accessdate=14 November 2019|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Boeing Crewed Flight Test]], Boeing's first crewed mission of their capsule\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Portal|Spaceflight}}\n{{Manned ISS flights}}\n{{Dragon spaceflights}}\n{{Falcon rocket launches}}\n{{Future spaceflights}}\n\n[[Category:Dragon 2]]\n[[Category:2020 in spaceflight]]\n[[Category:SpaceX payloads contracted by NASA]]\n[[Category:SpaceX human spaceflights]]\n[[Category:Future human spaceflights]]\n[[Category:2020 in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Erick Soares3", "label": "safe", "comment": "Ref corrected", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crew_Dragon_Demo-2"}
